article.headline: Portland 97, Oregon State 89 (2 OT)
article.story: CORVALLIS, Ore. (AP) -- Eugene Jeter had 11 of his 25 points after regulation as Portland held off Oregon State 97-89 in double-overtime Tuesday. David Lucas had a career-high 22 points on 10-of-16 shooting to lead the Beavers (1-1). Chris Stephens tied a career-high with 17. Donald Wilson had 23 points, eight assists and seven rebounds for the Pilots (1-1), who beat Oregon State on the road for the first time since the 1960-61 season. "We were on the short end in height and athleticism, but we were tough and competed," said Portland coach Michael Holton, whose team lost to Boise State last Saturday. "To lose your home opener and come out and beat a Pac-10 team, that's great." The two teams combined to put up 45 3-point attempts. Portland hit 12-of-24 and Oregon State was 7-of-21. Jeter and Adam Quick hit back-to-back 3-pointers to start a 13-5 run in the second overtime. Portland was a perfect 11-of-11 from the free throw line. Jeter was 5-of-7 shooting 3-pointers for Portland, which led by as many as 12 points. The Beavers trailed most of the game, until Stephens hit a running jumper with 5.4 seconds left in regulation to tie it at 69-69. Oregon State led 82-80 with 18 seconds left in the first overtime, but Jeter cut through the lane and scored to tie the game. Time expired on Stephens as he drove to the hoop for the Beavers. "We've got to feel disdain for the fact that one stop on defense in the first overtime would have changed everything," said Oregon State coach Jay John. Oregon State made several runs at the Pilots in regulation, but couldn't regain the lead until 75-73 in the first overtime. Portland led 26-13 at 8:45 in the first half. The Pilots made 10 of their first 16 shots, including 6-of-7 on 3-pointers. But Portland hit just 3-of-10 shots from there, and Oregon State went on an 18-10 run and cut the lead to 36-31 at halftime. Stephens hit a 3-pointer to get Oregon State within 46-45 with 14:39 left in the second half. But Donald Wilson put together consecutive three-point plays and Adam Quick made a long 3 to make it 55-45. The Beavers outrebounded Portland 43-35. Dustin Geddis had 17 points and nine rebounds for the Pilots.
